# component-contracts — Agent Rules

These rules apply to every task in this repository. Read them before making any changes.

---

## Core principle

**Contracts are authored before implementations.** Never write a component implementation without a corresponding `.contract.json` in `packages/contracts/src/`. The contract is the source of truth. The implementation is derived from it.

---

## Atomic Design

Structure all components according to Atomic Design:

- **Atoms** — single-purpose, no dependencies on other components (Button, Icon, Badge, Input)
- **Molecules** — composed of atoms, single responsibility (Accordion, SearchInput, FormField)
- **Organisms** — composed of molecules and atoms, complex UI sections (Header, DataTable, Form)
- **Templates / Pages** — layout-level, not part of this library

When authoring a contract, declare the atomic level in the `description` field. When implementing, place the component at the correct level — don't flatten everything into a single `components/` directory.

```
apps/web/src/
  atoms/
    button/
    icon/
    badge/
  molecules/
    accordion/
    form-field/
  organisms/
    ...
```

---

## Contracts

- One `.contract.json` per component in `packages/contracts/src/`
- Every contract must pass `pnpm validate` before implementation begins
- Contract `id` is kebab-case, matches the directory name in `apps/web/src/`
- `status` must be `draft` during initial authoring, promoted to `stable` only when implementation is complete and tested
- Token paths in contracts must reference semantic tokens, never primitives (use `brand.500`, not `color.blue.500`)
- Run `pnpm validate` after every contract change — never skip this

---

## Tokens

- **Never use raw values in CSS.** Every value in a component stylesheet must reference a CSS custom property generated by `@ds/tokens`
- Custom properties follow the pattern `--ds-{token-path}` with dots replaced by hyphens (e.g. `--ds-brand-500`, `--ds-space-md`)
- If a value you need doesn't exist as a token, add it to `packages/tokens/src/` first, rebuild tokens, then use it
- Never add one-off values to component CSS files

---

## Implementation (React / `apps/web`)

- Use `class-variance-authority` (CVA) for all variant-to-class mappings
- CVA variant keys must match contract prop names and values exactly
- Use `clsx` for conditional className merging
- Component props interface must be named `{ComponentName}Props` and exported
- Always use `forwardRef` — components must forward refs to their root DOM element
- Use semantic HTML — don't use `<div>` where a `<button>`, `<nav>`, `<section>` etc. is correct
- For complex interaction patterns (accordion, dialog, tooltip, dropdown), use the corresponding Radix UI primitive as the behavior layer and style it with tokens. Never hand-roll focus trapping, keyboard navigation, or ARIA state management.
- Component files: `{name}.tsx`, `{name}.css`, `{name}.stories.tsx`, `index.ts`

---

## Accessibility

- Every component contract must declare `accessibility.wcagLevel` — minimum `AA`
- Every component must have a declared ARIA `role` in its contract
- Keyboard interactions must be listed in `behavior.keyboardShortcuts` in the contract
- The `@storybook/addon-a11y` panel must show 0 violations on all stories before a component is considered done
- Focus management must follow the contract's `accessibility.focusManagement` declaration

---

## Storybook Stories

- Stories live in `{name}.stories.tsx` alongside the component
- Every contract variant must have a corresponding named story — no exceptions
- Story names match contract variant `displayName` values exactly
- Contract metadata (description, usage do/dont, version, status) is piped into the Storybook docs page — never write docs by hand in stories
- Interaction tests (`play` functions) are required for any story involving user interaction
- All stories must pass the a11y addon before merge

---

## Schema changes

- If a contract requires a field that doesn't exist in the schema, update `packages/schema/schema.json` first
- After any schema change, run `pnpm types:generate` to regenerate TypeScript types
- Document the schema change in `docs/decisions.md` as a new ADR
- Schema changes are breaking if they remove or rename existing fields — bump major version

---

## Versioning

- Use `pnpm changeset` to record changes before merging to main
- Contracts, schema, and tokens are linked — a breaking schema change bumps all three
- Never manually edit `CHANGELOG.md` files — changesets manages this

---

## CI

- All PRs must pass: `validate-contracts` → `build-tokens` → `test-web`
- Never merge with a failing CI run
- If you add a new package or app, add it to the CI workflow

---

## What not to do

- Don't write component CSS with raw hex values, pixel values, or named colors
- Don't create a component without a contract
- Don't write Storybook docs by hand — derive them from the contract
- Don't hand-roll keyboard navigation or focus management for complex components
- Don't merge contracts with `status: draft` to main without a plan to implement
- Don't skip `pnpm validate` before pushing contract changes

---

## Figma Library

### Agent prerequisite
Always load the `figma-use` skill before any `use_figma` call. Load `figma-generate-library` 
when building or updating variable collections or component sets. These skills own all 
Plugin API syntax rules — do not duplicate them here.

### Variable architecture
- Two collections: `Primitives` (raw values, mode: `Value`) and `Semantic` 
  (aliases → Primitives, mode: `Value`)
- Both collections have a ghost empty mode (all values = 0) created automatically by 
  the API — this is expected. Always call `setExplicitVariableModeForCollection` on 
  every component node and all children recursively to force the `Value` mode.
- Components bind exclusively to Semantic variables — never directly to Primitives
- Letter-spacing is not stored as a Variable — em units are incompatible with Figma 
  FLOAT. Handle via Text Styles only.
- Chained aliases are permitted: `border/brand → Semantic:brand/500 → Primitive:color/blue/500`

### Token architecture (3 tiers — enforced)
- Tier 1 Primitives: `packages/tokens/src/primitive/*.tokens.json` — raw values only
- Tier 2 Semantic: `packages/tokens/src/semantic/semantic.tokens.json` — aliases into Tier 1
- Tier 3 Component: `packages/tokens/src/component/{id}.tokens.json` — aliases into Tier 2
- Components (CSS, Figma, native) consume ONLY Tier 3 tokens. Never Tier 1 or 2 directly.
- Contracts reference Tier 3 token names in their `tokens` section.
- Adding a component requires: contract → component token file → CSS update → Figma styles.
  These four always move together. No partial updates.
- Figma paint styles are Tier 3: named `Button/Fill/Brand`, bound to Semantic variables.
  CSS output pattern: `--ds-button-fill-brand: var(--ds-brand-500)`

### Naming conventions
- Variables use `/` as group separator matching W3C DTCG: `color/blue/500`, `space/md`
- Components use `/` for Figma asset panel grouping: `Accordion/Item`, `Button/Primary`
- Component property names match contract prop names exactly: `variant`, `size`, `state`
- Paint styles named as `ComponentName/Role/Variant`: `Button/Fill/Brand`, `Button/Text/Inverse`


---


## Token architecture (3 tiers — enforced)
- Tier 1 Primitives: packages/tokens/src/primitive/*.tokens.json — raw values only
- Tier 2 Semantic:   packages/tokens/src/semantic/semantic.tokens.json — aliases into Tier 1
- Tier 3 Component:  packages/tokens/src/component/{id}.tokens.json — aliases into Tier 2
- Components (CSS, Figma, native) consume ONLY Tier 3 tokens. Never Tier 1 or 2 directly.
- Contracts reference Tier 3 token names in their tokens section.
- Adding a component requires: contract → component token file → CSS update → Figma styles.
  These four always move together. No partial updates.